## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern: **Timeout enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. This code uses it to kill a thread that exceeds a deadline — the fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work must **cooperate** — it needs the token to know when to stop |
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation natively |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` + `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | The CTS fires automatically after the deadline |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the modern cancellation signal |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cooperative cancellation doesn't forcibly inject exceptions |

---

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
The `work` delegate **must** check the token. If it doesn't, the timeout has no effect:
```csharp
// ❌ This will NOT stop on timeout — no token checks
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => ComputeForever(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ This will stop — token is checked in the loop
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    while (!done)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        ProcessNextChunk();
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. Pass the token through the full call chain.**
Every async/long-running method must forward it. One method that ignores the token blocks cancellation at that point.

**3. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.**
Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks.

**4. `Thread.Sleep` won't respond to cancellation.**
Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, token)`.

**5. Uncooperative code (can't modify to accept token).**
If you're wrapping a third-party call that ignores cancellation, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — there is no safe in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.

---

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// Before:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveQuery(connectionString),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After — pass the token into the work:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token => ExpensiveQuery(connectionString, token),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```
